[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] A **test fixture** is a device used to consistently test some item, device, or piece of software.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures are used in the testing of electronics, software and physical devices.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] In testing electronic equipment such as circuit boards, electronic components, and chips, a test fixture is a device or setup designed to hold the device under test in place and allow it to be tested by being subjected to controlled electronic test signals.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Examples are a bed of nails tester or smart fixture.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures can come in different shapes, sizes, and functions.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] There are several different types of test fixtures, including In-Circuit Test Fixtures, Functional Test Fixtures, and Wireless Test Fixtures.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] In Circuit Test (ICT) fixtures individually test each component on a PCB, while functional test fixtures assess the entire board's functionality.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Functional test fixtures simulate real-world conditions, whereas ICT is more focused on detecting assembly defects like short circuits or missing components.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] An In-Circuit Test fixture can come in both Inline and Standard variations.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] An Inline Test Fixture is designed for fast, automated testing directly within a production line, ideal for high-volume manufacturing where continuous testing maximises efficiency.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] A Standard Test Fixture, on the other hand, usually requires manual loading, making it well-suited to smaller-scale or specialised testing.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] In the context of software, a test fixture (also called "test context") is used to set up the system state and input data needed for test execution.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] For example, the Ruby on Rails web framework uses YAML to initialize a database with known parameters before running a test.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] This allows for tests to be repeatable, which is one of the key features of an effective test framework.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] In most cases, a custom test fixture will normally require custom test software.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] This software is created in order to ensure optimal testing performance and seamless integration.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] The custom software can be configured to carry out a number of different tests from BIST (Built-In Self Test) to advanced JTAG Implementation.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures can be set up three different ways: in-line, delegate, and implicit.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Delegate setup places the test fixture in a separate standalone helper method that is accessed by multiple test methods.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Implicit setup places the test fixture in a setup method which is used to set up multiple test methods.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] This differs from delegate setup in that the overall setup of multiple tests is in a single setup method where the test fixture gets created rather than each test method having its own setup procedures and linking to an external test fixture.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] The main advantage of a test fixture is that it allows for tests to be repeatable since each test is always starting with the same setup.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Test fixtures also ease test code design by allowing the developer to separate methods into different functions and reuse each function for other tests.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Further, test fixtures preconfigure tests into a known initial state instead of working with whatever was left from a previous test run.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] A disadvantage is that it could lead to duplication of test fixtures if using in-line setup.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] It is considered bad practice when implicit test fixtures are too general, or when a test method sets up a test fixture and does not use it during the test.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] A more subtle issue is if the test methods ignore certain fields within the test fixture.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Another bad practice is a test setup that contains more steps than needed for the test; this is a problem seen in in-line setup.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] A test case is considered "unsafe" when it modifies its fixture(s).
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] An unsafe test case can render subsequent tests useless by leaving the fixture in an unexpected state.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] It also causes the order of tests to be important: a modified fixture must be reset if more tests are to be run after an unsafe test.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Examples of fixtures include loading a database with a specific known set of data, erasing a hard disk and installing a known clean operating system installation, copying a specific known set of files, or the preparation of input data as well as set-up and creation of mock objects.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Software which is used to run reproducible tests systematically on a piece of software under test is known as a test harness; part of its job is to set up suitable test fixtures.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] In generic xUnit, a *test fixture* is all the things that must be in place in order to run a test and expect a particular outcome.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Frequently fixtures are created by handling *setUp()* and *tearDown()* events of the unit testing framework.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] In *setUp()* one would create the expected state for the test and in *tearDown()* it would clean up what had been set up.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] In physical testing, a fixture is a device or apparatus to hold or support the test specimen during the test.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] The influence of test fixtures on test results is important and is an ongoing subject of research.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Many test methods detail the requirements of test fixtures in the text of the document.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Some fixtures employ clamps, wedge grips and pincer grips.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Further types of construction include eccentric roller fixtures, thread grips and button head grips and rope grips.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Mechanical holding apparatuses provide the clamping force via arms, wedges or eccentric wheel to the jaws.
[src:junit5-java-lib/test-fixture] Additionally there are pneumatic and hydraulic fixtures for tensile testing that allow very fast clamping procedures and very high clamping forces.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing describes tests that are run at the unit-level to contrast testing at the integration or system level.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing, as a principle for testing separately smaller parts of large software systems, dates back to the early days of software engineering.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In June 1956 at US Navy's Symposium on Advanced Programming Methods for Digital Computers, H.D.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] It featured a specification-based approach where the coding phase was followed by "parameter testing" to validate component subprograms against their specification, followed then by an "assembly testing" for parts put together.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In 1964, a similar approach is described for the software of the Mercury project, where individual units developed by different programmers underwent "unit tests" before being integrated together.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In 1969, testing methodologies appear more structured, with unit tests, component tests and integration tests collectively validating individual parts written separately and their progressive assembly into larger blocks.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Some public standards adopted in the late 1960s, such as MIL-STD-483 and MIL-STD-490, contributed further to a wide acceptance of unit testing in large projects.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing was in those times interactive or automated, using either coded tests or capture and replay testing tools.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In 1989, Kent Beck described a testing framework for Smalltalk (later called SUnit) in "Simple Smalltalk Testing: With Patterns".
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In 1997, Kent Beck and Erich Gamma developed and released JUnit, a unit test framework that became popular with Java developers.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Google embraced automated testing around 2005–2006.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] A unit is defined as a single behaviour exhibited by the system under test (SUT), usually corresponding to a requirement.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] While a unit may correspond to a single function or module (in procedural programming) or a single method or class (in object-oriented programming), functions/methods and modules/classes do not necessarily correspond to units.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] From the system requirements perspective only the perimeter of the system is relevant, thus only entry points to externally visible system behaviours define units.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit tests can be performed manually or via automated test execution.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Automated tests include benefits such as: running tests often, running tests without staffing cost, and consistent and repeatable testing.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Testing is often performed by the programmer who writes and modifies the code under test.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing may be viewed as part of the process of writing code.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] During development, a programmer may code criteria, or results that are known to be good, into the test to verify the unit's correctness.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] During test execution, frameworks log tests that fail any criterion and report them in a summary.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] For this, the most commonly used approach is test - function - expected value.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Test cases underlie testing that is methodical rather than haphazard.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] A battery of test cases can be built to produce the desired coverage of the software being tested.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Formally defined test cases allow the same tests to be run repeatedly against successive versions of the software, allowing for effective and consistent regression testing.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] A test double is software used in software test automation that satisfies a dependency so that the test need not depend on production code.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] A test double provides functionality via an interface that the software under test cannot distinguish from production code.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] A parameterized test is a test that accepts a set of values that can be used to enable the test to run with multiple, different input values.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] A testing framework that supports parametrized tests supports a way to encode parameter sets and to run the test with each set.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Use of parametrized tests can reduce test code duplication.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Parameterized tests are supported by TestNG, JUnit, XUnit and NUnit, as well as in various JavaScript test frameworks.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Parameters for the unit tests may be coded manually or in some cases are automatically generated by the test framework.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In recent years support was added for writing more powerful (unit) tests, leveraging the concept of theories, test cases that execute the same steps, but using test data generated at runtime, unlike regular parameterized tests that use the same execution steps with input sets that are pre-defined.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Test code needs access to the code it is testing, but testing should not compromise normal design goals such as information hiding, encapsulation and the separation of concerns.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] To enable access to code not exposed in the external API, unit tests can be located in the same project or module as the code being tested.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In object oriented design this still may not provide access to private data and methods.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Therefore, extra work may be necessary for unit tests.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In Java and other languages, a developer can use reflection to access private fields and methods.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Alternatively, an inner class can be used to hold the unit tests so they have visibility of the enclosing class's members and attributes.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In the .NET Framework and some other programming languages, partial classes may be used to expose private methods and data for the tests to access.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] It is important that code solely for accommodating tests does not remain in the production code.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In C and other languages, compiler directives such as `#if DEBUG ... #endif` can be placed around such additional classes and indeed all other test-related code to prevent them being compiled into the released code.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] This means the released code is not exactly the same as what was unit tested.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] The regular running of fewer but more comprehensive, end-to-end, integration tests on the final release build can ensure (among other things) that no production code exists that subtly relies on aspects of the test harness.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] There is some debate among developers, as to whether it is wise to test private methods and data anyway.
