[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In test-driven development (TDD), unit tests are written before the related production code is written.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Starting with a failing test, then adds *just enough* production code to make the test pass, then refactors the code as makes sense and then repeats by adding another failing test.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing is intended to ensure that the units meet their design and behave as intended.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] By writing tests first for the smallest testable units, then the compound behaviors between those, one can build up comprehensive tests for complex applications.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] One goal of unit testing is to isolate each part of the program and show that the individual parts are correct.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] A unit test provides a strict, written contract that the piece of code must satisfy.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing finds problems early in the development cycle.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] This includes both bugs in the programmer's implementation and flaws or missing parts of the specification for the unit.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] The process of writing a thorough set of tests forces the author to think through inputs, outputs, and error conditions, and thus more crisply define the unit's desired behavior.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] The cost of finding a bug before coding begins or when the code is first written is considerably lower than the cost of detecting, identifying, and correcting the bug later.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Bugs in released code may also cause costly problems for the end-users of the software.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Code can be impossible or difficult to unit test if poorly written, thus unit testing can force developers to structure functions and objects in better ways.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing enables more frequent releases in software development.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] By testing individual components in isolation, developers can quickly identify and address issues, leading to faster iteration and release cycles.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing allows the programmer to refactor code or upgrade system libraries at a later date, and make sure the module still works correctly (e.g., in regression testing).
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] The procedure is to write test cases for all functions and methods so that whenever a change causes a fault, it can be identified quickly.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit tests detect changes which may break a design contract.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing may reduce uncertainty in the units themselves and can be used in a bottom-up testing style approach.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] By testing the parts of a program first and then testing the sum of its parts, integration testing becomes much easier.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Some programmers contend that unit tests provide a form of documentation of the code.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Developers wanting to learn what functionality is provided by a unit, and how to use it, can review the unit tests to gain an understanding of it.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Test cases can embody characteristics that are critical to the success of the unit.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] These characteristics can indicate appropriate/inappropriate use of a unit as well as negative behaviors that are to be trapped by the unit.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] A test case documents these critical characteristics, although many software development environments do not rely solely upon code to document the product in development.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In some processes, the act of writing tests and the code under test, plus associated refactoring, may take the place of formal design.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Each unit test can be seen as a design element specifying classes, methods, and observable behavior.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Testing will not catch every error in the program, because it cannot evaluate every execution path in any but the most trivial programs.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] This problem is a superset of the halting problem, which is undecidable.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Additionally, unit testing by definition only tests the functionality of the units themselves.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Therefore, it will not catch integration errors or broader system-level errors (such as functions performed across multiple units, or non-functional test areas such as performance).
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing should be done in conjunction with other software testing activities, as they can only show the presence or absence of particular errors; they cannot prove a complete absence of errors.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] To guarantee correct behavior for every execution path and every possible input, and ensure the absence of errors, other techniques are required, namely the application of formal methods to prove that a software component has no unexpected behavior.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] An elaborate hierarchy of unit tests does not equal integration testing.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Integration with peripheral units should be included in integration tests, but not in unit tests.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Integration testing typically still relies heavily on humans testing manually; high-level or global-scope testing can be difficult to automate, such that manual testing often appears faster and cheaper.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Software testing is a combinatorial problem.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] For example, every Boolean decision statement requires at least two tests: one with an outcome of "true" and one with an outcome of "false".
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] As a result, for every line of code written, programmers often need 3 to 5 lines of test code.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] This obviously takes time and its investment may not be worth the effort.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] There are problems that cannot easily be tested at all – for example those that are nondeterministic or involve multiple threads.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] In addition, code for a unit test is as likely to be buggy as the code it is testing.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Another challenge related to writing the unit tests is the difficulty of setting up realistic and useful tests.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] It is necessary to create relevant initial conditions so the part of the application being tested behaves like part of the complete system.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] If these initial conditions are not set correctly, the test will not be exercising the code in a realistic context, which diminishes the value and accuracy of unit test results.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] To obtain the intended benefits from unit testing, rigorous discipline is needed throughout the software development process.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] It is essential to keep careful records not only of the tests that have been performed, but also of all changes that have been made to the source code of this or any other unit in the software.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Use of a version control system is essential.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] If a later version of the unit fails a particular test that it had previously passed, the version-control software can provide a list of the source code changes (if any) that have been applied to the unit since that time.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] It is also essential to implement a sustainable process for ensuring that test case failures are reviewed regularly and addressed immediately.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] If such a process is not implemented and ingrained into the team's workflow, the application will evolve out of sync with the unit test suite, increasing false positives and reducing the effectiveness of the test suite.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit testing embedded system software presents challenges because the software is being developed on a different platform than the one it will eventually run on, making it difficult to run a test program in the actual deployment environment, as is possible with desktop programs.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] Unit tests tend to be easiest when a method has input parameters and some output.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] It is not as easy to create unit tests when a major function of the method is to interact with something external to the application.
[src:junit5-java-lib/unit-testing] For example, a method that will work with a database might require a mock up of database interactions to be created, which probably won't be as comprehensive as the real database interactions.
